1) $f(x + f(x + 2y)) = f(2x) + f(2y)$ for all integers $x, y$;

2) $f(0) = 2$.

3. (Petrovskii Dmitri) Let's designate through $P(n)$ - product of figures of the integer non-negative number $n$. To prove that sets A and B are unlimited, where:

(a) $A = \{\frac{P(n)}{P(n^2)}\}$, if $n$ belongs to set of such whole non-negative numbers that the number $n^2$ does not contain zero in the decimal record;

(b) $B = \{\frac{P(n^2)}{P(n)}\}$, if $n$ belongs to set of such whole non-negative numbers that the number $n$ does not contain zero in the decimal record.

